default1.1default 
defaultAction with Communities in Rural England (ACRE) is the national umbrella for 38 rural community-led regeneration 
defaultorganisations known as Rural Community Councils. ACRE itself was formed in 1987, but its members were created between 1920 and 2011, and so it 
defaultpossesses vast experience across the entirety of rural England with regard to devolved decision-making processes.
default&#xa0;
default1.2default 
defaultACRE is a charity and, together with the 38 Rural Community Councils, forms the ACRE Network.
default&#xa0;
default1.3default 
defaultACRE is co-financed by Defra to provid
defaulte information on the impact of government policies in rural areas. 
default The possibility of fiscal devolution to cities and city regions has potential impact on rural areas; we have noted disparities in how rural communities are served through existing devolved
default structures (
defaulte
default.g. Local Government, Local Enterprise Partnerships etc.) and wish to see all areas treated with equity. 
default&#xa0;
default1.4default 
defaultExamples of the work of the ACRE Network can be found in 
defaultMaking a Difference in rural communities throughout England
default - published jo
defaultintly by ACRE and Defra in the autumn of 2013.
default&#xa0;
default2. defaultSummarydefault&#xa0;default2.1default 
defaultOur response is brief, but we would be happy to share further information so as to support the work of the select committee.
